  <div id="about-questions">
    <h2>Our questions and research topics</h2>
    <p>
      The personnel files were created for the needs of the military at the time. They contain a wealth of information about social connections, economic attainment, and demographic behavior and experiences, that make them internationally significant for research.  
    </p>

    <p>
      Personnel records are particularly valuable for understanding New Zealand society in the early twentieth century. No other available historical source provides as much information about as many people. In North America, Britain, and Ireland, historical census manuscripts were retained to document the lives of ordinary people. But in New Zealand and Australia, the census returns were destroyed after the government had compiled its tabulations at the time. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Around half of the men eligible to serve in the military during World War I did so, representing 10 percent of the New Zealand population at the time. Questions in the personnel files about soldiers’ next of kin and employers extend the reach of the files beyond the men who served.   
    </p>

    <p>
      Measuring the ANZACs grows out of a project by an international team of researchers to measure and understand the health of New Zealanders since the 19th century. The researchers in the team had previously created a partial database of 24,000 New Zealand soldiers from World War I. Seeing the potential of this rich data source to answer their own questions and those of others, they plan to use this data to examine a range of questions about social and economic attainment and health. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="keyword">Stature and weight:</span> Our adult height reflects not only the genetic background of our ancestors, but also the conditions we lived in as children and teenagers when we were growing up. If economic or health conditions are particularly bad for a country, or groups within a country, the average height of the people affected often declines. Weight, too, reflects something about our economic and health environment, but closer to the time of measurement. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Men who served in the New Zealand Expeditionary Force had grown up in a wide variety of circumstances. Some were raised in rural towns and stayed there as farmers or farm laborers. Others grew up in the city, working in factories or offices. Still others were born into Māori communities, and grew up in a period where Māori lost a significant amount of land. New Zealand’s World War I soldiers has also experienced events such as the Russian flu epidemic of 1889, a depression in the 1890s, and a boom in export prices in the early twentieth century that influenced the food they could eat, the illnesses they suffered, and the jobs they did as teenagers and young men. By examining the height and weight of men with different backgrounds and experience, we can understand how healthy New Zealanders were in the early 20th century, and which groups had better or worse health. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="keyword">Death and survival:</span> The personnel files record the wounding, sickness, and deaths of men during service, and for many men who survived, they also record deaths well into the late 20th century. We know that many (16,302) of the men serving died in service or from wounds, and we know the battles in which they died. A complete database of soldiers and their deaths will help us understand what influenced men’s chance of death or survival during the war.  
    </p>
    <p>
      Although most of the soldiers returned, a very high proportion were wounded (40,362). We can use the information on soldiers’ background, wartime experiences, and when they died to understand how early adult health (recorded on the attestation forms) and wounds and disability (recorded on the history sheet) influenced how long soldiers lived after the war. Did men overcome their experiences, or were they affected through the rest of their lives? 
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="keyword">Migration:</span> The personnel records identify where a recruit was born, where he enlisted, the address of his current employer, and where he served. On some versions of the attestation form we find his parents’ birthplaces and his parents’ addresses. Taken together, these questions can provide significant information about migration into and around New Zealand between the time recruits were born and when they began service. For men who the research team link to death records, we have further information about migration. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="keyword">Social networks:</span> The records identify parents, spouses, and employers for most of the men who enlisted. Men are then followed into their military units. We can use this information to identify people who came into service together, and who served together and what happened to them. Researchers in the academy and community can connect this information with other research resources, such as newspaper reports in <a target="_blank" href="http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/">PapersPast</a>, to build up a deeper picture of social connections in early 20th-century New Zealand. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="keyword">Māori history:</span> Māori men served in the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/nga-pakanga-ki-tawahi-maori-and-overseas-wars/page-3">Pioneer Battalion</a>, yet the research team have seen records of men with Māori parents serving in other units. A complete database of the New Zealand World War I soldiers with parents and spouses’ names will allow us to see connections between Māori and Pākehā communities that are hidden in other sources. The database will also allow us to understand the social and economic standing of Māori men in this time period, such as what jobs they were doing and where they were living.
    </p>
