    <h2>ORGANIZATIONS</h2>
      <p>
      <span class="keyword">Archives New Zealand Te Rua Mahara o te Kāwanatanga</span><br><a target="_blank" href="http://archives.govt.nz/">Archives New Zealand</a> is the official archival agency of the New Zealand government, charged with preserving significant government records. It has branches in Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch, and Dunedin, and a growing digital presence. Archives New Zealand accepted the <a target="_blank" href="http://archives.govt.nz/world-war-one">World War I personnel files</a> from the <a href="http://www.nzdf.mil.nz/">New Zealand Defence Force</a> in 2006, after the passing of the last surviving New Zealand Expeditionary Force member. The records were the largest ever accession to the Archives New Zealand collection. Archives New Zealand completed scanning the entirety of the personnel files in 2014, in time for the centenary of the outbreak of World War I. Digital copies of all personnel files are available from Archives New Zealand on their Archway website. At the conclusion of the project Archives New Zealand will retain a copy of the complete database for preservation and integration with the images of the files. 
      </p>
      <p><span class="keyword">Auckland War Memorial Museum Tamaki Paenga Hira</span><br>The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.aucklandmuseum.com/">Auckland War Memorial Museum</a> was established in 1852. The Museum’s current building was opened in 1929 as a memorial to the men and women of the Auckland Province who had died during in the Great War. As well as honoring the contribution of New Zealanders who have served in armed conflicts, the Museum is the major historical and natural history museum for the Auckland region. The Museum engages with the public in creating Online Cenotaph, a database of individuals who served in the New Zealand military, as well as New Zealanders who have served in other international armed services. Online Cenotaph includes material similar to the Zooniverse data collection.</p>
      <p><span class="keyword">Zooniverse</span><br><a target="_blank" href="https://www.zooniverse.org">Zooniverse</a> was established in 2009 to use the efforts and ability of volunteers to help scientists and researchers deal with the flood of data that confronts them. It is a collaboration between universities and museums, led by the University of Oxford and the Adler Planetarium in Chicago, which creates citizen science and humanities projects. To date, more than a million people have used Zooniverse websites to discover planets, transcribe ancient papyri and keep an eye on plankton. Measuring the ANZACs builds on the team’s experience with Operation War Diary and the award-winning Old Weather project, which has mined more than a million pages drawn from 19th and early 20th century ship's logs in order to find information of interest to climate scientists and historians.</p>
      <p><span class="keyword">Minnesota Population Center</span><br>The <a target="_blank" href="https://www.pop.umn.edu/">Minnesota Population Center</a> at the University of Minnesota is the world’s leading creator and distributor of historical and contemporary demographic data, with public use data on more than two billion individuals from censuses and surveys from 1703 to the present. The Minnesota Population Center’s experience in cleaning, coding, harmonizing, and distributing socio-economic and health data will contribute to the creation of a public-use version of the data for use by researchers around the world.</p>

      <p><span class="keyword">Zooniverse@UMN</span><br>The "Measuring the ANZACs" project is partially funded by the Zooniverse@UMN initiative through the University of Minnesota’s Office of the Vice President for Research, the University Libraries, the Colleges of Biological Sciences, Liberal Arts, and Science & Engineering, and the University of Minnesota Informatics Institute.</p>
      
      <h2>TEAM</h2>
      <h4>Research:</h4>
      <p>
      Measuring the ANZACs builds on existing research with New Zealand military records by Kris Inwood (University of Guelph), Les Oxley (University of Waikato), and Evan Roberts (University of Minnesota). The team have used a smaller collection of New Zealand military records from World War I and other conflicts to study health and mortality in New Zealand since the mid-19th century. 
      </p>
      <p>
      <a target="_blank" href="http://www.evanroberts.net/">Evan Roberts</a> is a social and economic historian at the University of Minnesota. He grew up in New Zealand and taught at Victoria University of Wellington for four years. His research interests in soldiers in New Zealand, children’s growth, and women in work in America are more coherent than they first appear. Outside of history, Evan runs, takes photos, and listens to Bob Dylan, though rarely managing to combine all three of these interests.
      </p>
      <p>
      <a target="_blank" href="http://krisinwood.ca/">Kris Inwood</a> is a historian and economist at the University of Guelph who examines economy and health for indigenous and settler populations in Australia, Canada, New Zealand and South Africa. His most recent work, Lives in Transition: Longitudinal Analysis from Historical Sources (McGill-University Press 2015) builds on collaborations with family historians and combines genealogical and scholarly analysis. 
      </p>
      <p> 
      <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mngt.waikato.ac.nz/staff%20list/staffhome.asp?user=loxley">Les Oxley</a> is an economist and econometrician at the University of Waikato, New Zealand.  Born in the north of England, he spent 19 years at the University of Edinburgh, moving to New Zealand in 1996. His research interests are broad, including time series econometric theory, environmental history, scientometrics, economic history and the economic drivers of innovation. Les relaxes by walking his dogs, gardening, looking for the latest gadgets (especially those that are crowd-funded) and travelling.
